 To support this acquisition strategy, the program will follow an agile approach to develop capabilities and a robust DevSecOps (Development/Security/Operations)
 solution to deliver the capabilities. The Future Operationally Resilient Ground Evolution (FORGE) program is executing a software acquisition approach founded
 primarily on software and infrastructure reuse, partnerships with other programs, limited scope, use of existing contracts where necessary, and maximizing competition
 and flexibility in contracting. For the Mission Data Processing (MDP) thrust, the FORGE program is using competitive Other Transaction (OT) authorities to develop the
 software framework and applications. For the FORGE Command and Control (FC2) thrust, the FORGE team is using competitive OT authorities to develop Mission
 Management, Telemetry Command and Control, Ground Resource Management, and user interface software, while the mission unique software will be provided
 by the space vehicle contractors. For the Next-Gen Transition effort, the program is using the Next-Gen Geostationary Equatorial Orbit (GEO) and Next-Gen Polar
 contracts with the space vehicle prime contractors to perform the work needed to develop ground capabilities. The program is executing the MDP, FC2, and Next-Gen
 OPIR Interim Operations (NIO) thrusts within the scope of its acquisition authorities. The program is executing the Relay Ground Station (RGS) thrust using traditional
 acquisition authorities. Relay Ground Station - Asia (RGS-A) was designated an ACAT III by the MDA. All RGS activities will be consolidated with RGS-A to capture the
 RGS system as an ACAT II program.




