Note
This program, BA 5, PE 1206440SF, project 657111, Resilient Ground Architecture (RGA), is a new start.

A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Resilient Ground Architecture establishes a proliferated missile warning processing & data distribution ground architecture that holistically creates a robust day-today
operation with predictable and graceful degradation to a Survivable & Endurable mission—providing increased resilience through all phases of conflict and threat
spectrum. Fielding RGA capabilities meets/aligns with JROC-M 059-23, PPD-35/40, and CJCSI 3296.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                         FY 2025          FY 2026     FY 2027
Title: Resilient Ground Architecture (RGA)                                                                                                      0.000            0.000     110.300
Description: Resilient Ground Architecture (RGA) establishes a proliferated missile warning processing & data distribution ground
architecture that holistically creates a robust day-to-day operation with predictable and graceful degradation to a Survivable &
Endurable mission—providing increased resilience through all phases of conflict and threat spectrum. This development effort
resolves current stovepipe limitations and provides the scalable foundation necessary to deploy and manage a proliferated
network of ground locations. Fielding RGA capabilities meets/aligns with JROC-M 059-23, PPD-35, and CJCSI 3296.

FY 2026 Plans:
N/A
FY 2027 Plans:
Begin high value Mesh Data Transport and processing upgrades to connect MW assets and enable data distribution. Begin
stand up cloud infrastructure to establish central and edge-node compute processing. Start containerizing of missile warning
applications to enable globally accessible Missile Warning and Tracking (MWT) mission baseline and geographically-agnostic
baseline management. Start cloud proliferation to enable a MWT baseline globally accessible with high availability. Begin
technology maturation and risk reduction for S/E-capable communication antenna, mission antenna, and containerized processing
capabilities. Begin S/E prototype development: building prototype S/E node with pathway to delivering first operational S/E node.
