A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Space Systems Command is executing the Department of War (DoW) Space Test Program (Project 662617) through the Space Access and the Combat Power
Enterprise. As a result, the United States Space Force will advance the Department's space capabilities development through institutional processes, principled public
servants; space-minded warfighters; and bold and collaborative problem solvers.

This program falls within the Science and Technology (S&T) and Test & Evaluation (T&E) mission area which provides the S&T initiatives, demonstrations, experiments,
and studies towards developing next-generation space capabilities. The T&E mission area provides all efforts required to establish and operate the test infrastructure for
USSF capabilities. Program interdependencies include:
Defense Research Sciences (0601102SF); Major T&E Investments - Space (1206759SF); Small Business Innovation Research (1205502SF); Space Advanced
Tech Dev / Demo (1206616SF); Space Innov Intg & Rapid Tech Dev (1203174SF); Space Rapid Capabilities Office (1206857SF); Space Science and Technology
(1206310SF); Space Systems Prototype Transition (1206427SF); Space Technology (1206601SF); Space Test and Evaluation (1202051SF); University Research
Initiatives (0601103SF).

The Department of the Air Force (DAF), as the Department's designated Space Test Program (STP) Executive Agent (EA), provides a critical multi-user space program
that is essential for national security. America secures peace through strength, and that strength is built on the unyielding technological edge in space forged by strategic
investments in the STP. As the Department of War's (DoW) primary gateway for space experimentation, STP is a direct investment in deterring adversaries and ensuring
the nation's space superiority. STP provides the primary spaceflight capability to demonstrate, evaluate, and accelerate risk-reducing and advanced technologies in
operational space environments. STP is responsible for mission design, spacecraft acquisition, integration, launch, and on-orbit operations for emerging technologies
from the entire DoW research community, including the Army, Navy, Air Force, Space Force, National Reconnaissance Office, and other agencies. By centrally financing
these critical mission elements, STP offers the most cost-effective way to flight-test new space systems, technologies, and concepts.

Central to STP's mission is the DoW Space Experiments Review Board (SERB), which conducts a rigorous annual review to evaluate and prioritize space experiment
proposals to meet joint warfighter needs. This process ensures that STP focuses on cutting-edge technologies with direct military relevance, accelerating their
maturation into operational capabilities and providing our troops with a decisive advantage. This strategic approach enables DoW space researchers to:

•Demonstrate Feasibility: Prove the viability of new space systems and technologies through rigorous testing and evaluation, raising their Technology Readiness Levels.
•Improve Operational Design: Characterize the space environment and sensor physics to enhance operational systems and future upgrades.


