E. Acquisition Strategy
The Space Test Program (STP) employs a multi-faceted acquisition strategy designed to maximize taxpayer dollars, cultivate a dynamic space industrial base, and
leverage commercial, government, and academic partners. This strategy supports space research experiments which are developed, financed, and delivered by
various service research laboratories and Department of War (DoW) agencies, and prioritized annually by the independent DoW Space Experiments Review Board
(SERB). STP then seeks out the most cost-effective means of spaceflight to maximize the number of experiments flown within the constraints of priority, opportunity, and
available funding. For experiments with requirements that cannot be satisfied by auxiliary payload opportunities, STP procures dedicated spacecraft and launch vehicle
hardware within the constraints of available funding and according to experiment requirements. These include small and medium launch vehicle-class satellites, as well
as small launch vehicle-class boosters and commercial rideshares (previously procured under PE 1206860SF). Medium launch vehicle-class boosters from National
Security Space Launch (NSSL) under PE 1206853SF provide medium launch as required. If a service fails to adequately fund a particular experiment, if STP deems
the experiment impractical to fly, or if the appropriate spaceflight opportunity becomes unavailable, STP shifts remaining resources to provide spaceflight support for
the next highest priority experiment. STP also leverages National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) investments and contracting vehicles, such as using
a Task Order on NASA's Research, Engineering & Mission Integration Services (REMIS)-2 contract. STP continues to explore innovative contracting mechanisms, like
AFWERX's Strategic Funding Increase, and collaborates with partners like the Air Force Research Lab to leverage existing contracts.




