A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The 6th Sustainment Squadron is developing, prototyping, deploying, sustaining and operating Defensive Cyber Operations - Space (DCO-S) (Project 673070) for
Guardians across Combat Power, Enterprise Management and Information Technology, Space Domain Awareness, Launch, Position Navigation and Timing, Satellite
Communications, Weather, and Science & Technology and Test & Evaluation. As a result, the Service will deter, neutralize, defeat and/or destroy counterspace
threats, improve readiness and operational reach of existing force structure, integrate Allies, partners, and commercial space to USSF units which will result in resilient
Infrastructure, equipment, and personnel.

The Defensive Cyberspace Operations Space (DCO-S) program delivers advanced defensive cyber capabilities to safeguard United States Space Force (USSF)
mission systems, including their computer systems, software applications, spacecraft and sensitive operational data against unauthorized access, corruption, or
destruction. The program develops and deploys defensive cyberspace capabilities, network security, damage assessment and recovery, cyber threat detection and
mitigation, and active response strategies to address evolving threats and changes in the cyber environment. The program is transitioning Space Vehicle Defense from
demonstration and development to deployment. These objectives are achieved through research, development, testing, and acquisition in areas such as proactive
defense, defensive counter cyberspace, cyberspace intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance (ISR), command and control situational awareness, persistent
network operations, decision support, recovery, and digital forensics. In addition, this program element supports the integration, testing and sustainment of classified
efforts to enable advanced USSF cyberspace warfare operations. The program is managed by the 6th Sustainment Squadron (6 STS) under Mission Delta 6.

The FY 2027 request increases significantly to more than double planned DCO-S deployments, including the added responsibility for mission system integration efforts,
fully funds the Space Vehicle Defense project to pivot from development to deployment, and integration, testing and sustainment of classified efforts to enable advanced
USSF cyberspace warfare operations.

DCO-S employs a Development/Security/Operations (DEVSECOPS) framework for ground segment tool development, leveraging the Software Acquisition Pathway
(SWP) Adaptive Acquisition Framework. This approach integrates security best practices into modern development workflows and toolchains. The program focuses
on two primary product lines: Manticore(Detect & Identify) and Kraken(Protect & Respond). These tools aim to establish shared platform, infrastructure, and data layer
solutions to support open frameworks and architectures across the enterprise ground portfolio. Both Manticore and Kraken utilize open-source and commercial tools,
customized to address space-specific requirements such as protocol analytics. Due to the unique nature of USSF systems, tailored solutions are necessary to address
threats effectively, as no commercial off-the-shelf products meet these specialized needs.



