catalogue, and identify objects and activities in the space domain. As the foundation for space control, SDA encompasses surveillance of all space objects and activities;
detailed surveillance of specific space assets; monitoring space environmental conditions; monitoring cooperative space assets; gathering indications and warning
on adversary space operations; and conducting integrated command, control, communications, processing, analysis, dissemination, and archiving activities. Space
Force investment program interdependencies include: RDT&E Budget Line Items: Space Domain Awareness/Planning/Tasking SW (1208248SF); Automate Sat C2
(1207440SF); Space Situational Awareness Operations (1203940SF); Space Situational Awareness Systems (1206425SF); and elements of Procurement Budget Line
Item: Space Mods (SPCMOD). This is not a new start.

 Space Systems Command (SSC) System Delta (SYD) 85 and the Kronos Program Office are continuing to develop the Kronos Family of Systems for Guardians across
 Warfighting, Operational Command, and Combat Support units. As a result, the Service will improve battle management of all weapon systems and adjust force
 structure as required. Combat Forces Command (CFC) Mission Delta 2 (MD2) is developing, sustaining and modernizing SDA for Guardians across MD2, USSF and
 other users. As a result, the Service will deliver SDA capabilities, improve readiness and operational reach of the existing force structure, and integrate Allies, partners,
 and commercial space to USSF units.

 The Space Domain Awareness (SDA)/ Planning/ Tasking software program is an Office of the Secretary of War (OSW) pilot initiative in which all lifecycle funding
 is tracked under Budget Activity 8 (BA 8), Software and Digital Technology Pilot Programs, beginning in FY 2021. This pilot program enables the execution of
 modern software development practices encompassing development, procurement, sustainment, modification, and maintenance activities within a single Research,
 Development, Test and Evaluation (RDT&E) appropriation in this Program Element (PE).

 SDA/Planning/Tasking functions support United States Space Force (USSF) and U.S. Indo-Pacific Command (USINDOPACOM). Capabilities will initially be delivered
 to Combat Forces Command (CFC) and U.S. Space Forces - Space (S4S). The SDA/Planning/Tasking software program provides a collaborative environment that
 will enhance and modernize SDA and Battle Management Command and Control (BMC2) capabilities; create decision-relevant views of the space and multi-domain
 environment; rapidly detect, track, and characterize objects of interest; identify / exploit traditional and non-traditional sources; perform space threat analysis; and
 enable efficient distribution of data across the Space Surveillance Network (SSN). The program maintains enterprise infrastructure, platform, and data services, and
 develops mission applications to enable responsive, resilient operational-level SDA/Planning/Tasking capabilities for the National Space Defense Center (NSDC),
 Combined Space Operations Center (CSpOC), Mission Delta 2 (MD 2), other Command and Control (C2) centers, and Space Force Components within Combatant
Software and Digital Technology Pilot Programs
 Commands. The employment of an agile-based Rapid Delivery Framework (RDF) with a 120 day Program Increment (PI) construct fosters a collaborative and integrated
 environment for the community to effectively plan and deliver C2 capabilities. The enterprise-wide system provides a common government infrastructure and processes
 to allow C2 capabilities at USSF Mission and Combat Deltas to rapidly address the evolving and dynamic threat. The program also identifies shared/common platform,
 infrastructure, and data layer solutions to support open frameworks and architectures across the enterprise ground portfolio. Funding includes technical studies,
 development, experimentation, integration, and related support costs.

 For FY 2027, the Space Domain Awareness/Planning/Tasking SW Program Element increased $415.071 million from the FY 2026 funding level. For Project 68A035, FY
 2027 funding reflects a significant increase to fully fund enterprise SDA development and sustainment, driven by USSPACECOM priorities and transfer of O&M funding
 for current SDA systems from PE 1203940SF to BA 8 RDT&E project 68A035 to support agile software development. Activities in Project 68A035 are continuing from
 FY 2026 and are not a new start. For Project 681018, funding was transferred from Project 68A035 to this project (also known as Kronos) and substantially increased for
 a total of $260.441 million in FY 2027 to expand development of BM and C2 scope previously in SDA. Activities in Project 681018 are not a new start. This is consistent
 with the direction and intent of the Under Secretary of War for Acquisition and Sustainment in splitting the Space Domain Awareness (SDA) and BMC2 programs out of
 the Space C2 program as documented in a 12 May 2025 Acquisition Decision Memorandum.

 This program element may include necessary civilian pay expenses required to manage, execute, and deliver weapon system capability. The use of such program funds
 would be in addition to the civilian pay expenses budgeted in program elements 1206392SF and 1206398SF.

 This program is in Budget Activity 8, Software and Digital Technology Pilot Program because this budget activity includes funding provided for expenses necessary for
 agile development, test and evaluation, procurement, production and modification, and the operation and maintenance of these programs.$$, $$Mission Delta 2 (MD2) 2nd Sustainment Squadron is maintaining, sustaining, developing, and modernizing SDA for Guardians across MD2, USSF and other users. As
a result, the Service will deliver SDA capabilities, improve readiness and operational reach of the existing force structure, and integrate Allies, partners, and commercial
space to USSF units.

 Space Domain Awareness (SDA)/Planning/Tasking functions support the United States Space Force (USSF) and U.S. Indo-Pacific Command (USINDOPACOM).
 Capabilities will initially be delivered to USSF Combat Forces Command (CFC) and U.S. Space Forces - Space (S4S). The SDA/Planning/Tasking software program
 provides a collaborative environment that will enhance and modernize SDA and Battle Management Command and Control (BMC2) capabilities; create decision-relevant
 views of the space and multi-domain environment; rapidly detect, track, and characterize objects of interest; identify/exploit traditional and non-traditional sources;
 perform space threat analysis; and enable efficient distribution of data across the Space Surveillance Network (SSN). The program maintains enterprise infrastructure,
 platform, and data services, and develops mission applications to enable responsive, resilient operational-level SDA/Planning/Tasking capabilities for Mission Delta
 2 (MD 2), the National Space Defense Center (NSDC), Combined Space Operations Center (CSpOC), and other Command and Control (C2) centers. Employing an
 agile-based Rapid Delivery Framework (RDF) with a 90-day Program Increment (PI) construct, fosters a collaborative and integrated environment for the community to
 effectively plan and deliver C2 capabilities. The enterprise-wide system provides a common government infrastructure and processes to allow C2 capabilities at USSF
 operational Deltas to rapidly address the evolving and dynamic threat. The program also identifies shared/common platform, infrastructure, and data layer solutions to
 support open frameworks and architectures across the enterprise ground portfolio. Funding includes technical studies, development, experimentation, integration, and
 related support costs.

