                                                                                                                     FY 2025   FY 2026    Base       OOC          Total
limited to, Data as a Service, Zero Trust Architecture, Platform Support, Continuous Improvement/Continuous
Deployment (CI/CD) toolchain, and infrastructure and inherent sustainment efforts that are an integral part of
the agile software development process. Other activities include dedicated Systems Engineering & Integration
(SE&I), Test & Evaluation (T&E), Model Based Systems Engineering (MBSE) and prototype Validation &
Verification to support these efforts.

FY 2026 Plans:
Plan and develop a message standard compliant open architecture to support both the Space Domain
Awareness (SDA) and Theater Support missions to meet dynamic emerging threats. Develop product support
and enhancements for operationally accepted applications, workflows, and capabilities, and SDA collection
processing software (observation processing, orbit determination and propagation) necessary to publish the
satellite catalog. Establish machine-to-machine interfaces for common and dynamic SDA event processing
(Satellite Conjunction Assessment, Rendezvous & Proximity Operations, and Space Threat Processing).
Evaluate and implement necessary upgrades to legacy SDA systems to allow integration into the modern
SDA suite. Continuously improve integrated messaging and sensor support/tasking capabilities. Scale product
support and enhance Theater Support software applications to include Intelligence, Integration, Priorities, and
Objectives, tasking and Orders Generation, Status of Forces, Space Effect Coordination, Theater Situational
Awareness, and Operational Support. Carry out development, system engineering and contracting efforts to
integrate commercial, contractor, and government applications through the release of multiple incremental
software capability in FY 2026.

Rapidly respond to implement system resiliency and situational awareness necessary to operate in the
contested space domain. Activities may include, but are not limited to program office support, studies, technical
analysis, experimentation, risk reduction, prototyping, and activities that may leverage commercial, U.S.
Government partnership, and international opportunities to respond to existing and emerging adversarial threats
with speed and agility.
FY 2027 Base Plans:
Develop software and enabling infrastructure for:

Automation and Advanced Processing: Increasing automation in observation processing, orbit determination,
uncorrelated track processing, and other key areas to improve efficiency and accuracy in detecting, tracking, and
identifying space objects, including closely spaced objects and those in cis-lunar space.

