D. Acquisition Strategy
The Battle Management and Command and Control software program is employing agile software development practices in the Software Acquisition Pathway (SWP)
Planning Phase effective May 2025, in accordance with direction from the Undersecretary of War for Acquisition and Sustainment, with plans to enter the Execution
Phase in FY 2026. The program adheres to multiple Capability Needs Statements as well as a Software Initial Capabilities Document. BMC2 maintains cradle-to-
grave research, development, and operational support for software baselines predominantly using agile software development methods, as software development is
continuous and never enters a discrete sustainment phase. BMC2 is leveraging Department of War guidance by maximizing the use of Commercial Solutions Opening
(CSO) and Other Transaction business approaches to quickly leverage commercial solutions with minimal tailored development to the maximum extent practical. Similar
to Enterprise Space Domain Awareness, this program also generally acquires tools and capabilities through an agile-based Rapid Delivery Framework that delivers and
sustains new features and capabilities through a Continuous Improvement/Continuous Deployment (CI/CD) pipeline with 90-day Program Increments; however, there
are several current systems and/or new commercial applications that may not follow this model. The acquisition strategy emphasizes modular contracting, commercial
innovation, and continuous delivery, leveraging flexible mechanisms like Commercial Solutions Openings (CSOs) and Other Transaction Agreements (OTA) to engage
both traditional and non-traditional vendors. The program maintains a strong Intellectual Property (IP) strategy to secure sufficient data rights while balancing cost
realities of commercial solutions and licensing. The program positions itself in the role of the integration manager, employing multiple contractors working together to
deliver a single architecture without relying on a government or contractor as the integrator approach.




