A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The Department of War (DoW) faces growing threats to its use of the Electromagnetic Spectrum (EMS) from peer and near-peer adversaries. Operations are further
complicated by debilitating electromagnetic interference from friendly forces operating without coordination in the same environment. These significant challenges are
compounded by the Department's reliance on manual, siloed, and non-interoperable legacy EMS systems and processes.

 Overlapping legacy tools and capabilities are housed in disparate environments and managed by both the Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA) (e.g.,
 Electromagnetic Battle Management-Joint (EMBM-J) and Global Electromagnetic Spectrum Information System (GEMSIS)) and the Services (e.g. Automated
 Communications Engineering System (ACES) and Systems Planning, Engineering, and Evaluation Device (SPEED)). In FY 2027, the DoW is investing in EMS
 Information Technology (EMS IT) modernization, consolidating these spectrum tools and capabilities into a single artificial intelligence-enabled platform – Maven Smart
 Systems (MSS). MSS is a comprehensive, Software as a Service-based enterprise data operating system designed to integrate, manage, and analyze data from
 disparate sources in support of U.S. military operations. MSS serves as a central hub connecting raw data, analytics, and artificial intelligence/machine learning models
 to real-world military operations. The initial work in FY 2027 will focus on migrating DISA-owned capabilities, with an emphasis on EMBM-J.

 EMS IT modernization will replace legacy spectrum management capabilities and apply automation and artificial intelligence to enable joint force commanders to
 coordinate, synchronize, and integrate the use of EMS across the full range of military operations, by providing robust and integrated spectrum management, Situational
 Awareness (SA), Command and Control (C2), and Decision Support (DS). Further, by transforming the EMS into a truly agile, resilient, and intelligently managed
 domain, EMS IT Modernization will provide the critical EMS end-to-end data layer for Combined Joint All-Domain Command and Control (CJADC2), enabling the rapid,
 secure, and uninterrupted flow of information necessary for decision advantage to achieve EMS superiority in any conflict.

 EMS IT modernization principles are outlined in the 2026 National Defense Strategy, 2023 Department Data, Analytics, and Artificial Intelligence Adoption Strategy,
 and 2020 Department of War Electromagnetic Spectrum Superiority Strategy (EM SSS). Capability development and modernization also align with Joint Staff validated
 requirements derived from combined Joint Force Commander (JFC)/Joint Task Force (JTF), Military Departments (MILDEPs), Services, and Combatant Command
 (CCMD) requirement needs under 2025 Joint Requirements Oversight Council Memorandum (JROCM) 070-25 Modern Electromagnetic Spectrum Information
 Technology Environment, 2023 JROCM 23-007 U.S. Strategic Command 2023 Electromagnetic Spectrum Operational Assessment, 2020 Joint Publication 3-85 Joint
 Spectrum Operations, and 2020 JROCM 086-20 Electromagnetic Battle Management.




